    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 4.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And Jehoahaz besought the Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "besought the face of the Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 13:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the comment ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ad loc",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). Jehoahaz, as Josephus says, \"betook him-serf to prayer and supplication of God, entreating that he would deliver him out of the hands of Hazael, and not suffer him to continue subject\" ('Ant. Jud.,' 9:8. § 5). He did not turn from his sin of idolatry, perhaps did not suspect that it was this sin which had provoked God's anger; but in a general way he repented, humbled himself, and besought God's mercy and assistance. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And the Lord hearkened unto him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " God accepted his repentance, all imperfect as it was, so far as to save the people from the entire destruction with which it was threatened by the severe measures of Hazael (ver. 7), to continue the national existence (ver. 23), and ultimately to restore the national prosperity (ver. 25 and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 14:25-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
